This is billiards player Calvin A. Demarest - national amateur billiard champion.

1909 NY Times Article: <a href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C00E6DC1438E033A25757C0A9649D946897D6CF">query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C00E6DC1438E033A...</a>

&quot;Calvin A. Demarest of Chicago is the world's champion at 18.2 balk line billiards. He won the title last night by overwhelmingly defeating his fellowtownsman, George Sutton, a former champion, at Madison Square Garden Concert Hall, by the score of 500 to 78. Young Demarest exhibited confidence bordering on recklessness, essaying shots that no one but a most experienced player would attempt.&quot;

1912 NY Times Article
<a href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C0CE7DF153CE633A25751C1A9629C946396D6CF">query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C0CE7DF153CE633A...</a>

&quot;HOPPE RETAINS 18.2 BILLIARD TITLE; Calvin Demarest Defeated in Hotel Astor Ball Room by 500 Points to 440.&quot;

and a 1915 NY TImes article:
<a href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9E0CE7DC1038E633A25754C1A9609C946496D6CF">query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9E0CE7DC1038E633A...</a>

&quot;CHICAGO, June 16. -- Calvin Demarest, former national amateur billiard champion, attacked his wife with a pocket knife today and then slashed his own throat. His mother, who attempted to restrain him, was cut on the hand. Husband and wife were taken to a hospital.&quot;
